### 🔐 Phase 3 · File Integrity Verification `(T+90 min → T+4 hours)`

> Goal: Establish exactly what data was accessed, copied, archived, and exfiltrated.

#### 3a. Identify Staged / Accessed Files

- [ ] **Audit recently accessed files on `{{ source_ip | default("<source_host>") }}`** – Find all files accessed in the `{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }}`-hour window preceding detection:
  ```bash
  # Linux – find files accessed since detection window
  find / -not -path "/proc/*" -not -path "/sys/*" \
    -atime -{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }} \
    -type f -ls 2>/dev/null | sort -k8 -r | head -100 \
    > /tmp/accessed_files_{{ source_ip | default("host") }}.txt

  # Filter for sensitive paths
  grep -E "{{ sensitive_paths | default('/home|/var/www|/etc|/opt|/data') }}" \
    /tmp/accessed_files_{{ source_ip | default("host") }}.txt
  ```

- [ ] **Identify archive/compression activity** – Look for recently created archives (data staging):
  ```bash
  # Find ZIP, TAR, RAR, 7z files created in the window
  find / -not -path "/proc/*" -not -path "/sys/*" \
    -mtime -{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }} \
    \( -name "*.zip" -o -name "*.tar*" -o -name "*.rar" \
       -o -name "*.7z" -o -name "*.gz" \) \
    -ls 2>/dev/null > /tmp/archives_{{ source_ip | default("host") }}.txt
  cat /tmp/archives_{{ source_ip | default("host") }}.txt

  # Windows – PowerShell
  Get-ChildItem -Recurse -Include *.zip,*.tar,*.rar,*.7z `
    | Where-Object { $_.LastWriteTime -gt (Get-Date).AddHours(-{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }}) } `
    | Select-Object FullName, LastWriteTime, Length | Export-Csv /tmp/archives.csv
  ```

{% if affected_files is defined and affected_files %}
- [ ] **Verify integrity of flagged files** – Run cryptographic hash against the known-good baseline for each affected file:

  | File / Path | Expected SHA256 | Current SHA256 | Status |
  |---|---|---|---|
{% for f in affected_files %}
  | `{{ f }}` | Run against CMDB baseline | `sha256sum {{ f }}` | ☐ Verify |
{% endfor %}

{% else %}
- [ ] **Build file hash inventory** – Hash all files in sensitive directories and compare with AIDE/Tripwire baseline:
  ```bash
  # Generate current hashes
  find {{ sensitive_data_path | default("/data /home /var/www") }} \
    -type f -exec sha256sum {} \; 2>/dev/null \
    > /tmp/current_hashes_$(date +%s).txt

  # Compare with AIDE baseline
  aide --check --config /etc/aide/aide.conf \
    2>&1 | grep -E "changed|removed|added" \
    > /tmp/aide_delta_$(date +%s).txt
  ```
{% endif %}

#### 3b. File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) Review

- [ ] **Review FIM alerts for the exfiltration window**:
  ```bash
  # AIDE – check for changes in sensitive directories
  aide --check --config /etc/aide/aide.conf

  # Wazuh / OSSEC FIM alerts
  grep "Integrity checksum" /var/ossec/logs/alerts/alerts.log | \
    grep "$(date -d '-{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }} hours' +%Y/%m/%d)" | head -50

  # Windows – Auditpol + Get Security Event Log
  Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='Security'; Id=4663} `
    | Where-Object { $_.TimeCreated -gt (Get-Date).AddHours(-{{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }}) } `
    | Select-Object TimeCreated, Message | Export-Csv /tmp/fim_events.csv
  ```

- [ ] **Identify deleted files / anti-forensics** – Check for deliberate evidence destruction:
  ```bash
  # Linux – check for recently shredded / wiped files
  grep -r "shred\|wipe\|dd if=/dev/zero\|secure-delete" \
    /var/log/auth.log /var/log/syslog /var/log/bash_history 2>/dev/null

  # Check bash history for data-staging commands
  cat /home/*/. bash_history /root/.bash_history 2>/dev/null | \
    grep -E "zip|tar|scp|curl|wget|ftp|nc|netcat|base64|openssl enc"

  # Recover recently deleted files (if possible)
  # foremost -t all -i /dev/<disk> -o /tmp/recovered/
  ```

- [ ] **Check SIEM for file-access audit events** – Pull all 4663/4660 (Windows) or `audit` (Linux) file-read/delete events:
  ```bash
  # Linux – auditd
  ausearch -k sensitive_data_access --start {{ audit_period_hours | default(72) }} hours ago \
    -i > /tmp/auditd_file_access.txt

  # grep for exfil-pattern commands
  ausearch --start today -m execve -i | \
    grep -E "curl|wget|scp|ftp|nc|python.*socket|b64encode"
  ```

- [ ] **Verify data-at-rest encryption** – Confirm that sensitive files on `{{ source_ip | default("<source_host>") }}` are encrypted at rest (BitLocker/LUKS):
  ```bash
  # Linux – check LUKS
  lsblk -o NAME,FSTYPE,MOUNTPOINT | grep -i crypto
  # Windows
  manage-bde -status C:
  ```

